Here are the MSTest attributes/patterns for each scenario (requires MSTest 3.9+):

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class HardwareTests
{
    // 1. Windows-only (registry access)
    [TestMethod]
    [OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
    public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
    {
        // Skipped automatically on non-Windows
    }

    // 2. Skip in CI (requires local GPU)
    [TestMethod]
    [CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
    public void RenderFrame_ProducesExpectedOutput()
    {
        // Only runs locally, skipped in CI
    }

    // 3. Flaky external API — retry up to 3 times
    [TestMethod]
    [Retry(3)]
    public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
    {
        var result = await _client.GetForecastAsync();
        Assert.IsNotNull(result);
    }

    // 4. Cleanup temp files even on failure — use [TestCleanup]
    private string? _tempFile;

    [TestMethod]
    public void Export_WritesToTempFile()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
        File.WriteAllText(_tempFile, "data");
        // ... assertions ...
    }

    [TestCleanup]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        if (_tempFile is not null && File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Scenario | Attribute | Min Version |
|----------|-----------|-------------|
| OS-specific | `[OSCondition(...)]` | 3.10 |
| Skip in CI | `[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]` | 3.10 |
| Flaky retry | `[Retry(N)]` | 3.9 |
| Guaranteed cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` | Any |

`[TestCleanup]` runs after every test method regardless of pass/fail, making it ideal for resource cleanup. Alternatively, implement `IDisposable` or `IAsyncDisposable` on the test class for the same guarantee.
